\par
This is coherent and the logic tracks. The core claim \u8212? true tree minimizes forced extra losses \u8212? is a valid parsimony argument. But let me push on four specific things:\par
\par
{\b 1. "Losses are rare" is load-bearing and contestable.} Loss rates are highly heterogeneous across lineages. Cteno genomes in particular show extensive lineage-specific loss \u8212? they're exactly the kind of clade where this method could be misled. Parsimony under high-loss regimes has known failure modes (analog to long-branch attraction). The method needs to either (a) be robust to rate heterogeneity, (b) explicitly model it, or (c) flag uncertainty when rates are high.\par
\par
{\b 2. Independence assumption is probably wrong.} 1000 orthogroups is NOT 1000 independent observations:\par
\li360  \u8226?  Orthogroups share genome-assembly fate (incomplete assembly \u8594? many co-absent)\par
\li360  \u8226?  Physical clustering (losses in same chromosome region co-occur)\par
\li360  \u8226?  Pathway-level loss (you lose one, the rest become dispensable)\par
\li360  \u8226?  The "effective number of independent characters" could be ~50\u8211?100, which changes the law-of-large-numbers math materially.\par
\par
{\b 3. This looks a lot like Dollo parsimony.} Dollo is specifically designed for presence/absence characters where gain is rare/unique and loss is possible multiple times. That's exactly the orthogroup-origin scenario. So the question is: is this a new method, or is it {\b "Dollo parsimony applied rigorously to modern genomic orthogroups at scale, using the OCL framework's loss-at-origin vs continued-absence distinction"}? The latter is still valuable and defensible, but the novelty framing should be about data + rigor + scale, not a new parsimony principle.\par
\par
{\b 4. Validation test:} Before claiming this resolves contested nodes, show it recovers KNOWN-resolved nodes. Mammals are well-resolved, arthropods are well-resolved. Run this on species70 and ask: does it correctly place primates, or does it place some cteno-species-equivalent loss-heavy lineage wrongly? If it fails on settled relationships, the deep-node claim is moot.\par
\par
{\b What I think holds up:}\par
\li360  \u8226?  Alignment-independence is a real and valuable niche\par
\li360  \u8226?  Scale (genome-wide orthogroup matrix) is a real advantage over traditional parsimony\par
\li360  \u8226?  The OCL distinction (loss_at_origin vs continued_absence) is a meaningful refinement \u8212? standard Dollo doesn't make this\par
\par
{\b What I think needs careful claiming:}\par
\li360  \u8226?  Not "new method" \u8212? "rigorous application of Dollo-style parsimony with modern genomic data + refined event accounting"\par
\li360  \u8226?  Sensitivity analysis to lineage-specific loss rates is table stakes before publishing\par
\li360  \u8226?  Discordance flagging is probably more scientifically honest than picking a "winner"\par
\par
Your thoughts on the lineage-specific-loss concern specifically? That's the one I think could kill it if unaddressed.\par
