Your responses are good \u8212? let me recalibrate:\par
\par
{\b Point 1 (lineage heterogeneity):} You're partially right and I under-credited you. Losses that appear under ALL 105 candidate trees cancel out of the ranking \u8212? what matters is topology-dependent loss differences. A high-loss lineage's raw loss count contributes to the score's magnitude but not necessarily its ranking bias. I'd still want to see this quantified (split losses into topology-invariant vs topology-contingent and confirm heterogeneity lives mostly in the former), but the logic is defensible.\par
\par
{\b Point 2 (independence):} You made a distinction I missed \u8212? you're talking about independence of {\b origins}, not independence of {\b loss events}. Origins are genuinely independent evolutionary events. Loss correlation is real but biases score magnitude more than ranking. I partly retract my concern. Partly \u8212? because co-loss across correlated orthogroups can still bias ranking toward trees where the correlation-generating lineages happen to cluster. But you're right that the origin-independence framing is the right unit of analysis.\par
\par
{\b Point 3 (novelty framing):} You're right, I was reductive. Parsimony/Dollo is the algorithmic kernel \u8212? ancient, uncontroversial. The {\b framework} is:\par
\li360  \u8226?  Orthogroup-as-evolutionary-feature (alignment-free phylogenetic unit)\par
\li360  \u8226?  OCL's refined event accounting (loss_at_origin vs continued_absence)\par
\li360  \u8226?  Systematic evaluation against enumerated meaningful topologies from trees_species\par
\li360  \u8226?  Genome-scale aggregation with per-feature traceability\par
\par
That IS novel as an integrated approach. Comparing to "molecular phylogenetics uses likelihood": the statistical principle is classical, but the framework around it (substitution models, partitioning, etc.) is where the field lives. Same shape here.\par
\par
{\b "Table stakes":} Poker term \u8212? the minimum you have to put in to be dealt into the hand. Figuratively: the bar below which reviewers won't take a submission seriously. A sensitivity analysis to heterogeneous loss rates would be a reviewer's first concern \u8212? without it, manuscript gets bounced before substantive evaluation. Not optional; not nice-to-have; the price of entry.\par
\par
{\b Ties and uncertainty:} Totally tractable. Borrow from tree-building tradition \u8212? bootstrap-analog: subsample orthogroups, compute loss scores, see which trees stably rank high; confidence bands around top-ranked trees; "structure_007 is best with 95% of subsamples" vs "best tie between 3 structures."\par
