{\b On your proposed filter \u8212? "all unresolved clades represented" (or all-but-one):} Good instinct, but note a subtle point:\par
\par
\li360  \u8226?  {\b All 5 clades represented}: the orthogroup was present at the LCA of all 5 \u8594? its parsimony score is {\i identical or near-identical} across all 105 topologies. These orthogroups carry no differentiating signal \u8212? they're confirming but not discriminating.\par
\li360  \u8226?  {\b All-but-one (4/5 clades)}: this is where the signal actually lives. The missing clade must have either lost it or never had it, and WHERE that missing clade sits in a candidate topology changes the implied loss events. Best discriminating orthogroups.\par
\li360  \u8226?  {\b Fewer than 4}: more discriminating signal {\i per orthogroup} but higher LBA risk.\par
\par
So the filter strategy might be: {\b weight or gate by representation pattern}. The 4/5 orthogroups are the sweet spot. The 5/5 orthogroups act as noise-reducing "controls" that should score equal across topologies (if they DON'T, that itself is a diagnostic flag).\par
\par
