Gene families as a third data type fits the framework cleanly \u8212? same mechanics (AGS-based presence/absence), different scale of signal, same alignment-free advantage. Natural extension.\par
\par
{\b Where they add value that orthogroups miss:}\par
Gene families capture ancient homology that spans multiple orthogroup-level subfamilies. An ion-channel gene family's origin event sits at a DEEPER node than any of its constituent TRPA/TRPV/TRPC orthogroups' origins. For the 105 topology ranking, deeper events in the ambiguous zone carry just-as-useful signal for distinguishing topologies \u8212? and sometimes more, if the ambiguous nodes are themselves deep.\par
\par
{\b Scale distinction \u8212? and the phylogenetic implication:}\par
\par
\par
{\f1\fs18 | Level | Origin typically sits at | Signal for cteno/porifera/plac/cnid/bilateria ambiguous zone |}\par
{\f1\fs18 |-------|--------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------|}\par
{\f1\fs18 | Gene family | Deep \u8212? often pre-Metazoan or Metazoan root | Often in the ambiguous zone \u8594? carries topology signal |}\par
{\f1\fs18 | Orthogroup | Shallower \u8212? usually within a clade or at a subfamily origin within Metazoa | May or may not \u8212? depends on origin depth |}\par
\par
\par
So gene families are MORE LIKELY to contribute topology-relevant origin events than orthogroups on average, for the specific ambiguous nodes species70 permutes.\par
\par
{\b On the dedup rule "gene family > orthogroup" \u8212? one refinement to consider:}\par
\par
An orthogroup's origin can be at the same node as its parent gene family (redundant, drop) OR at a deeper/more-recent node than its parent (distinct event). Specifically, orthogroup origin \u8805? gene family origin \u8212? never earlier, because the orthogroup is a subset of the family.\par
\par
Cases:\par
\li360  \u8226?  {\b Gene family origin in ambiguous zone, orthogroups with origins inside clades}: gene family wins, drop orthogroups (they contribute no topology signal anyway \u8212? origins inside clades are invariant across the 105)\par
\li360  \u8226?  {\b Gene family origin before ambiguous zone, orthogroups with origins IN ambiguous zone}: KEEP the orthogroups, the gene family contributes no topology signal\par
\li360  \u8226?  {\b Both have origins coinciding at the same ambiguous-zone node}: redundant, gene family wins\par
\par
So the refined rule: {\b prefer the feature whose origin event lands in the ambiguous zone}. When both have ambiguous-zone origins at the same node \u8594? gene family wins (your preference, based on pipeline rigor). When one does and the other doesn't \u8594? keep the one that does.\par
\par
This also naturally integrates with the 4/5 clade representation filter from earlier \u8212? features with origins in the ambiguous zone are exactly those with 4/5 or 5/5 representation (conserved across or past the deepest ambiguous node but with variation at shallower ambiguous nodes).\par
\par
{\b Practical implication:} dedup has to be done at the {\i event} level (where does this feature's origin sit?) rather than at the {\i entity} level (is it a gene family or orthogroup?). Slightly more bookkeeping, cleaner signal.\par
\par
Does that nuance land, or do you want to keep the simpler "gene family > orthogroup" rule and accept some signal loss?\par
