HGNC gene groups as a bootstrap source for gene family data is elegant \u8212? expert-curated, broad coverage, sidesteps the labor of building RGS sets from literature gene by gene. Let me make sure I understand the hazard properly:\par
\par
{\b Why incomplete functional sets break the pipeline:}\par
\par
The trees_gene_families algorithm (as I understand it from a quick read of the AGS/CGS/RGS convention) assumes the RGS captures the full homology scope of a family \u8212? every homolog in the target species genome should be findable from at least one RGS member via BLAST/HMM. If the HGNC group is an INCOMPLETE functional set (say, 6 of the 12 ion channel families), then:\par
\li360  \u8226?  Real homologs in species genomes belonging to the 6 missing families won't be pulled in (no RGS seed to find them)\par
\li360  \u8226?  These show up as "absent" when they're actually present, just unreachable from the RGS\par
\li360  \u8226?  Signal becomes: "we see ion channels wherever the 6 seed families happen to reach" \u8212? confounded with RGS choice\par
\par
For STEP_2's presence/absence signal, this is contaminating: an HGNC group with incomplete coverage would report false absences in species that have the family but a subfamily the RGS missed.\par
\par
{\b Confirming the scope:} ~2000 HGNC groups total; the triage is deciding which are safe (bona fide gene families, even if broad superfamilies with full coverage) vs. risky (functional mixes with partial family representation). A one-afternoon manual curation pass for 2000 entries is ~8 seconds each \u8212? plausibly doable if you can skim a group's description and member list.\par
