{\b\fs26 Claude}\par
\par
Your concern is sharper than I credited earlier. The "category-level dedup" from before (Pfam wins domains, orthogroups wins families, etc.) assumes the categories don't overlap at the sequence level \u8212? but they do. A Pfam domain hit at residues 50\u8211?150 of gene X and a gene-family BLAST hit on the same gene X anchored on the same conserved region are the same phylogenetic signal reported twice. My earlier "truly orthogonal" hierarchy was too optimistic.\par
\par
{\b Your coordinate-level solution is the principled answer, and it's deferrable:}\par
\par
The proper dedup: intersect coordinate ranges per gene across tools. If Pfam call at [50,150] and gene-family BLAST hit at [40,160] overlap substantially, they're one signal. Pick the higher-ranked tool for that coordinate range, drop the other. This catches cryptic duplication the category-level rule misses.\par
\par
But you're right to defer \u8212? implementing coordinate tracking in gene families + overlap-detection logic is meaningful engineering on top of STEP_2's already-substantial scope. Not now.\par
\par
{\b Standalone-per-tool analysis as the development path is smart:}\par
\par
Treating each tool's feature set as an independent parsimony analysis gives us:\par
\par
\li360  1. {\b Per-tool structure ranking} \u8212? each tool produces its own top-ranked topology and confidence\par
\li360  2. {\b Cross-tool concordance} \u8212? if orthogroups AND gene families AND Pfam all vote structure_007, that's strong. If they disagree, we've found something\par
\li360  3. {\b Diagnostic value on disagreement} \u8212? where tools disagree, we can investigate whether tool-specific bias (HMM library coverage, BLAST window length, seed choices) explains the split\par
\li360  4. {\b Sensitivity check} \u8212? if structure_007 wins regardless of tool, the signal is robust. If different tools pick different winners, either we have genuine biological heterogeneity OR cryptic-duplication-adjusted methodology matters\par
\par
That last point is actually a {\i better} outcome than integrating everything \u8212? if independent analyses converge, you have stronger evidence than a single integrated analysis could provide, because each tool contributes an independent perspective on the same question.\par
\par
{\b Implication for STEP_2 design:}\par
\par
STEP_2 becomes tool-parameterized: given a feature matrix from ANY tool (orthogroups / HGNC / Pfam / PANTHER / future), produce structure ranking with uncertainty. Run it multiple times (once per tool), then a thin downstream comparator reports:\par
\li360  \u8226?  Per-tool top structure + uncertainty\par
\li360  \u8226?  Concordance matrix across tools\par
\li360  \u8226?  Consensus if any\par
\par
Coordinate-level integration = future research direction (valuable enough to be a paper in itself \u8212? "how much of your gene-content phylogenetic signal is cryptically duplicated across annotation tools?").\par
\par
{\b Before we move on} \u8212? one question: when you say "stick to each tool as a stand-alone assessment," do you mean:\par
(a) Run STEP_2 separately for orthogroups, separately for HGNC, separately for Pfam \u8212? 3 separate runs with 3 separate outputs\par
(b) Run STEP_2 once with a pooled feature matrix (tool is just metadata), and the COMPARISON happens downstream\par
(c) Something else\par
\par
My instinct is (a) \u8212? cleaner per-tool output \u8212? but (b) is also defensible.\par
